      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I can help with that. A \"confidentiality period\" is a time frame during which the parties involved in a contract agree to keep certain information secret. Think of it as a period of time where you and your partner decide not to share the details of your secret recipe with anyone else. On the other hand, a \"survival clause\" is a provision in a contract that keeps certain terms or conditions in effect even after the contract has ended. It's like a pact you make with your friend to still share your secret recipe with them even after the contract period is over. So, the main difference is that one is about keeping information private for a certain time, while the other is about keeping certain terms in place after the contract ends.",
